\emph default
.
 Note that any map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathbb{S}\rightarrow\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, through the similarity transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}=[\,]\circ\mu\circ[\,]^{-1}$
\end_inset

; likewise, a function of the reals can be restated as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The permutation group elements acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 are given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Permutation Elts"

\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}(x)$
\end_inset

 is discontinuous, but only on a countable set of points.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}(x)$
\end_inset

 is discontinuous on the proverbial 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

set of measure zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and so one can easily form well-defined integrals using classical techniques.
 
\end_layout

