\begin_layout Section
A Remarkable Shadow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical evaluation of sums requires a certain amount of cross-checking
 so as to catch errors.
 A particularly curious sum to evaluate is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta_{N}(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-\frac{s}{N}\;\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\left(\frac{2n+1}{2N}\right)^{s}\]

\end_inset

which does no permutation at all.
 That is, one effectively has 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{N}(s)=\zeta_{N;p,p}(s)$
\end_inset

 for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The limiting integral is trivial to calculate, since 
