\begin_layout Standard
This section explores analytic approaches to evaluating the integral 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zeta-permute"

\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,q}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a peicewise combination of Mobius functions 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\]

\end_inset

it is enough to evaluate the indefinite integral 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx\]

\end_inset

This integral does not have any simple, closed-form solution, but can be
 given in terms of an infinite sum.
 This may be obtained via the Newton series 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(1+x\right)^{s}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\dbinom{s}{k}x^{k}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\binom{s}{k}=\frac{\Gamma\left(s+1\right)}{\Gamma\left(k+1\right)\Gamma\left(s-k+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

is the binomial coefficient.
 The series is absolutely convergent on the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

 that we wish to explore.
 The indefinite integral may then be evaluated as a sum:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
F\left(s,\alpha;x\right)= & \int\frac{x^{s}}{x+\alpha}dx\\
= & \int\frac{\left(y-\alpha\right)^{s}}{y}dy\\
= & \left(-\alpha\right)^{s}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\binom{s}{k}\left(\frac{-1}{\alpha}\right)^{k}\int y^{k-1}dy\\
= & \left(-\alpha\right)^{s}\left[\ln\left(x+\alpha\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{k}\binom{s}{k}\left(1+\frac{x}{\alpha}\right)^{k}\right]\end{align*}

\end_inset

This allows the Mobius integral to be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx=\frac{a}{c}F\left(s,\frac{d}{c};x\right)+\frac{b}{c}F\left(s-1,\frac{d}{c};x\right)\]

\end_inset

Using that fact that, in general, for coninued fractions, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 will be integers, with 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=\pm1$
\end_inset

, one may re-write the above as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx=\frac{\left(-d\right)^{s-1}}{c^{s+1}}\left[\mp\ln\left(x+\frac{d}{c}\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{k}\binom{s-1}{k}\left(1+\frac{cx}{d}\right)^{k}\left(\frac{\pm s+kbc}{k-s}\right)\right]\label{eq:mobius sums}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1,2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, this can be made more explicit.
 So, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{1,2}\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{1}+r}}\]

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+r}}\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\left\lfloor 1/x\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=\left\lfloor x/\left(1-a_{1}x\right)\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 integers.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and replacing, one gets
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{1,2}\left(x\right)=\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
a= & 1+a_{1}\left(a_{2}-a_{1}\right)\\
b= & a_{1}-a_{2}\\
c= & \left(a_{2}-a_{1}\right)\left(1+a_{1}a_{2}\right)\\
d= & 1+a_{2}\left(a_{1}-a_{2}\right)\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset

 for all possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This form is valid over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(\underline{x},\overline{x}\right)=\left(\frac{a_{2}}{1+a_{1}a_{2}},\frac{1+a_{2}}{1+a_{1}+a_{1}a_{2}}\right)\]

\end_inset

and so one may combine these elements to write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}S_{1,2}\left(x\right)x^{s-1}dx=\sum_{a_{1}=1}^{\infty}\sum_{a_{2}=1}^{\infty}\int_{\underline{x}}^{\overline{x}}\frac{ax+b}{cx+d}x^{s-1}dx\label{eq:analytic sum}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point, the ability to perform any further simple manipulations stops.
 The summations are only conditionally convergent; one cannot interchange
 the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 with the sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If one were to do so, one would quickly discover that, for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are logarithmically divergent.
 While this is not immediately obvious just be gazing at the sums, it is
 easily confirmed by numerically evaluating them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One more avenue suggests itself, but then fails: one migh consider applying
 the binomial expanstion to the powers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1+\frac{x}{\alpha}\right)^{k}$
\end_inset

 that appear in the sum for 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(s,\alpha;x\right)$
\end_inset

, and then exchanging the order of summations there.
 But this is not possible; the sums fail outright.
 Thus, it appears that there are no further (obvious) analytic techniques
 that one can apply to reduce the expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytic sum"

\end_inset

.
 One is then left to contemplate the numeric evaluation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytic sum"

\end_inset

.
 Naively, one might expect that doing so would offer considerable advantages
 over the numeric sum 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zeta-pq-sum"

\end_inset

, but this is not at all the case; convergence is even slower, and fails
 more profoundly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of both the sums 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zeta-pq-sum"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytic sum"

\end_inset

 to locate the position of the first non-trivial zero is examined in the
 next section.
 
\end_layout

